o3 Answer:
Rewrite the general term so its growth is easy to see:  

aₙ = 2ⁿ / 3^{n/2}  
     = (2²)^{n/2} / 3^{n/2}  
     = (4/3)^{n/2}  
     = ( √(4/3) )ⁿ .

Because 4/3 > 1, the factor (4/3)^{n/2} grows without bound as n → ∞. Hence  

lim_{n→∞} aₙ = ∞.  

(The limit is not zero; in fact it diverges to infinity, so in the sense of the divergence test the limit “does not exist” as a finite number.)

Since the limit of the terms is not 0, the divergence (n-th term) test applies and tells us that the series Σ aₙ diverges.

o4-mini Answer:
First rewrite the term  
\[
2^{-2\ln n} \;=\; e^{-2\ln n\;\ln2}
\;=\;n^{-2\ln2}\,.  
\]  
Hence  
\[
n\,2^{-2\ln n}
= n\;n^{-2\ln2}
= n^{\,1-2\ln2}
= \frac1{n^{\,2\ln2-1}}\,.  
\]  
So the series is a \(p\)\!--series  
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty n\,2^{-2\ln n}
=\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac1{n^{p}}
\quad\text{with}\quad
p=2\ln2-1\approx0.386<1.
\]  
Since \(p\le1\) the \(p\)\!--series diverges.

For the \(p\)-series with \(a_n =1/n^2\), take \(f(t)=1/t^2\). Then the integral‐test remainder estimate gives

\[
R_{1000} \;=\;\sum_{n=1001}^\infty\frac1{n^2}
\;\le\;\int_{1000}^\infty\frac{dt}{t^2}
\;=\;\Bigl[-\tfrac1t\Bigr]_{1000}^{\infty}
\;=\;\frac1{1000}\;=\;0.001.
\]

Hence after 1000 terms the “tail’’ of the series is at most \(10^{-3}\). In particular

\[
\sum_{n=1}^{1000}\frac1{n^2}
=\zeta(2)-R_{1000}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\sum_{n=1}^{1000}\frac1{n^2}
\;\;>\;\;\frac{\pi^2}{6}-0.001\approx1.643934.
\]
